yet unappreciated role in ending the Cold War. Grassroots and government nuclear abolitionists shifted U.S. and Soviet nuclear arms control paradigms from arms limitation to arms reduction. This paved the way for the reversal of the U.S.-Soviet nuclear arms race, which began with the landmark 1987 Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty. European peace activists also influenced Gorbachev’s “common European home” initiative and support for freedom of choice in Europe, which prevented the Soviet leader from intervening to stop the 1989 East European revolutions. These revolutions ripped the fabric of the Iron Curtain, which had divided Europe for more than four decades.Despite their inability to eliminate nuclear weapons, grassroots and government nuclear abolitionists deserve credit for playing a pivotal role in the Cold War’s endgame. They also provide a model for enacting dramatic, positive change in a peaceful manner.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAntinuclear movement. 0aCold WarxDiplomatic history. 0aNuclear disarmament. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 4aHistory-Contemporary 1950 to the present. 4aHistory-Military. 4aPoli Sci-International Relations. 4aPoli Sci-U.S. Foreign Policy. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century / Cold War.2bisacsh  a1980s.  aAmerican foreign relations.  aCold War.  aEastern Europe.  aEurope.  aFreeze movement.  aGermany.  aIron Curtain.  aMikhail Gorbachev.  aRonald Reagan.  aRussia.  aSoviet Union.  aUnited States.  aanti-nuclear movement.  aarms race.  aarms reduction.  ademonstrations.  adiplomacy.  aend of the Cold War.  agrassroots activist.  ainternational global abolition movement.  anon-proliferation.  anuclear abolition.  anuclear disarmament.  anuclear weapons.  apeace offensive.  apolitical history.  asocial move